Impacts of a government shutdown

Effects on government employees
    •    Furloughs: Many "non-essential" federal employees are put on temporary, unpaid leave.
    •    Working without pay: "Essential" employees, such as law enforcement, military personnel, and air traffic controllers, are required to work without pay during the shutdown. Federal contractors, however, are typically not guaranteed back pay.
    •    Back pay: Historically, Congress has passed legislation to retroactively pay federal workers once the government reopens. 
Effects on the public and services
    •    Reduced services: Many federal services and facilities close or operate with severe delays. This can include:
    ◦    National Parks and Museums: Many facilities and visitor centers close. While some parks may remain accessible, services like restrooms and trash collection cease.

    ◦    Federal Agencies: Routine functions like processing applications for passports, visas, and loans are delayed.

    •    Economic disruptions: Shutdowns can damage the economy by causing:
    ◦    Delayed economic reports from federal agencies, affecting investors.
    ◦    Interruptions in federal contract work.
    ◦    Reduced GDP growth, with losses increasing the longer a shutdown lasts.

    •    Continued services: Some programs continue with minimal disruption, such as Social Security and Medicare benefit payments, as they are mandatory spending programs funded outside of the annual appropriations process. However, some ancillary services like customer support may be affected. The U.S. Postal Service and the Federal Reserve are also generally unaffected because they have their own funding streams
